# where zig fits in the c & rust discussion


# the one-line positioning

# - c:    trust the programmer; minimal abstractions; manual everything.
# - rust: never trust the programmer; the compiler proves memory safety; rich
#         type system.
# - zig:  trust the programmer, but give them better tools; no hidden control
#         flow, no hidden allocations, explicit everything.
#
# zig is essentially "c done right in 2025" — not "rust done lighter." that's
# the key distinction.


# what zig actually does differently

# 1. no hidden control flow. no operator overloading, no exceptions, no
#    destructors, no implicit conversions. if a function call is on the page,
#    that's the only thing happening. (rust has Drop, Deref, panics — zig has
#    none.)
# 2. allocators are explicit. every function that allocates takes an allocator
#    as a parameter. there's no global malloc you accidentally call. you can
#    swap in a test allocator that detects leaks, an arena allocator for
#    short-lived work, a fixed-buffer allocator with no heap at all.
# 3. `comptime` instead of macros / generics. compile-time code is just zig
#    code that runs at compile time. generics are functions that take types as
#    values. no separate macro language, no separate trait system.
# 4. first-class c interop. @cImport literally parses c headers and gives you
#    the types directly — no ffi declarations, no bindgen step. zig can compile
#    c and c++ files; `zig cc` is a drop-in cross-compiler that many projects
#    (including bun) use as their c toolchain.
# 5. no memory safety guarantees at compile time. zig has runtime safety checks
#    in debug builds (bounds, overflow, ub) but no borrow checker.
#    use-after-free is still possible.


# where zig is winning

# - bun (js runtime competing with node) — written in zig, partly because
#   `zig cc` made cross-compilation trivial.
# - ghostty (mitchell hashimoto's terminal emulator) — zig.
# - tigerbeetle (financial database) — zig, leaning on explicit-allocator for
#   predictable performance.
# - river, uxn, lots of game-dev and embedded experiments.
# - as a c/c++ cross-compiler — `zig cc` is used by projects that aren't
#   otherwise written in zig at all (e.g. uber's go cross-compilation).


# where zig loses to rust

# - memory safety. rust gives a compile-time proof; zig gives better tooling
#   and discipline. for security-critical code (kernels, browsers, parsers
#   handling untrusted input), rust is the safer pick.
# - ecosystem. rust has crates.io with ~150k libraries; zig has a few hundred.
#   the package manager arrived in 2024 and is still maturing.
# - stability. zig is pre-1.0 (0.14 as of late 2025). the language still
#   changes between releases. rust has been stable since 2015.
# - hiring. "rust developer" is a job title; "zig developer" is a hobby
#   project.


# where zig beats rust

# - simplicity. you can learn zig in a weekend. rust takes months to be
#   comfortable with.
# - compile times. significantly faster, especially with the new self-hosted
#   compiler.
# - iterating on existing c code. @cImport a c header, write new code in zig,
#   link them together. no rewrite required.
# - cross-compilation. zig's killer feature. `zig build -Dtarget=...` just
#   works, from anywhere, with no extra toolchain setup. even rust users
#   sometimes use `zig cc` as their linker.
# - embedded. smaller binaries than rust, no runtime, no allocator unless you
#   ask for one.


# the mental model

#                  C            Zig          Rust
# abstraction     low           low          high
# safety          manual        manual+      compile-proven
# ecosystem       enormous      tiny         large
# learning curve  medium        low          steep
# who reaches     systems devs  systems devs systems devs who
# for it          from 1985     who want     want guarantees
#                               better c
#
# zig is the c person's upgrade path.
# rust is the c person's escape hatch.


# realistic outcome

# probably zig replaces neither c nor rust. instead:
# - rust keeps the security-critical-systems slot it's already winning
#   (kernels, browsers, crypto, network parsers, cloud infra).
# - zig carves out a niche where rust feels like overkill: tooling, game
#   engines, embedded, codec / dsp work, projects that need to interop heavily
#   with c.
# - c stays where c already is — and the new generation of "c-style" projects
#   splits between zig and modern c (c23+).


# zig vs c ergonomics — point by point

# build system
# - zig replaces make / cmake / autotools with build.zig — a regular zig file
#   that describes your build. just code: variables, conditionals, functions.
#   no dsl, no separate language, no .in templates, no m4.

# cross-compilation
# - the killer feature, not exaggerated. on any host:
#     zig build -Dtarget=aarch64-linux-musl
#     zig build -Dtarget=x86_64-windows-gnu
#     zig build -Dtarget=riscv64-linux-gnu
#     zig build -Dtarget=wasm32-wasi
#   works out of the box. no toolchain install, no sysroot fiddling, no
#   CROSS_COMPILE= env vars, no docker. zig bundles libc sources (musl, glibc,
#   mingw, wasi-libc) and builds them on demand.
# - this is so good that non-zig projects use `zig cc` as their c/c++
#   cross-compiler (uber's go cross-compilation, for one).

# macros
# - zig has none. instead it has comptime:
#     fn max(comptime T: type, a: T, b: T) T {
#         return if (a > b) a else b;
#     }
# - that's the generics story AND the macro story — one mechanism. compile-time
#   code is just normal zig code the compiler runs at build time. no #define,
#   no token pasting, no preprocessor.

# package manager
# - arrived in 0.11 (2023), matured through 0.14. build.zig.zon is the manifest
#   (think Cargo.toml), dependencies fetched by url + hash, no central registry
#   yet (deliberate — they want it to mature first). fine — not as polished as
#   cargo, but worlds better than "vendor a tarball into third_party/".


# bonus ergonomic wins

# - `zig cc` is a working c compiler. use it as a gcc/clang replacement in
#   existing makefiles today — no zig code involved. great way to dip a toe in.
# - @cImport directly parses c headers. point at stdio.h or libcurl/curl.h and
#   you get the types and functions, no ffi bindings, no bindgen.
# - defer instead of cleanup goto. `defer file.close();` runs at scope exit.
#   replaces the whole `goto cleanup;` pattern in c.
# - errors are values, not exceptions. `!T` is "T or error." compiler forces
#   you to handle them. no silent errno, no exception-tables.


# honest tradeoffs

# 1. pre-1.0. 0.14 as of late 2025. language still changes between releases —
#    usually small, occasionally annoying. 1.0 targeted but not dated.
# 2. small ecosystem. need a json library? stdlib has one. need a postgres
#    driver? maybe. be ready to bind to c libraries (easy via @cImport, but
#    still work).
# 3. no memory safety guarantees. can still leak, use-after-free, double-free.
#    zig gives better tools (GeneralPurposeAllocator catches leaks/uaf in debug
#    builds, runtime bounds-checking, defined integer overflow) but no
#    compile-time proof.
# 4. standard library is in flux. good but still being shaped. things move.


